R Notebook

This is an example of how to update the cover art of GA using generative art. This is a cover from 1970:

An update would be colorful, but still make references to geographically relevant stuff! Tanaka contours sounds like a lovely idea.

I will use the following packages:

library(elevatr) # To get elevation data
library(MexBrewer) # Color palettes
library(metR) # For contouring

19.1783° N, 98.6427° W Use {elevatr} to get elevation data:


izta <- get_elev_raster(locations = data.frame(x = c(-98.61, -98.665), 
                                               y = c(19.13, 19.215)),
                        z = 10, 
                        prj = "EPSG:4326",
                        clip = "locations")

 Accessing raster elevation [-------------------------]   0%
 Accessing raster elevation [=========================] 100%
Mosaicing & Projecting
Warning: multiple methods tables found for ‘direction’
Warning: multiple methods tables found for ‘gridDistance’
Clipping DEM to locations
Note: Elevation units are in meters.

Convert to {terra} SpatRaster object and thereof to data frame:

izta <- rast(izta)

izta <- as.data.frame(izta, 
                      xy = TRUE) %>%
  rename(elev = 3)

Plot contours; use Hiroshige palette from {MetBrewer}:

Repeat plot but now with Tanaka countours:

ggplot(data = izta,
       aes(x, y, z = elev)) +
  geom_contour_filled(breaks = seq(min(izta$elev), 
                                   max(izta$elev), 
                                   length.out = 11)) +
  geom_contour_tanaka(sun.angle = 260, 
                      smooth = 10) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = cols) +
  coord_equal() + 
  theme_void() + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")

ggsave("itza-tanaka-contours.png",
       width = 4,
       height = 7,
       units = "in")
